With the recent Amazon acquisition of food giant Whole Foods for $13.7 billion, and the share price hitting the $1 000 mark, investors are wondering whether the Amazon case extends to further tech share opportunities. The internet book-seller began trading at just under $2/share in May 1997 and anyone who bought $10 000 of shares at that price and hung on for two decades, would have a holding of close to $5 million (that&#8217;s a 49 000%-plus return). But finding the right stocks and holding on to them during difficult periods is not easy.Juan Torres Rodriguez, research analyst, Schroder ISF Global Recovery Fund, says that for every tech start-up success story, there are hundreds of other such businesses that have failed in the process.Read: Amazon robots poised to revamp how Whole Foods runs warehouses